When there are Korean characters on review comments, it gets displayed as question mark. The value is also stored as question mark in the database column. This only happens when external database mySQL is used. The comments appears properly when the built in HSQLDB is used. 

Sample Korean characters used during testing:-
{noformat}
테스트입니다
{noformat}

The current sending review reminder option in the review uses the same email subject as the one used when sharing the review -- also, the message text doesn't get sent.

Sharing review email subject:-
{noformat}
[Crucible] user shared the review CR-1 with you
{noformat}

Sending review reminder email subject:-
{noformat}
[Crucible] user shared the review CR-1 with you
{noformat}

It would be good if the review reminder email have a different email subject.

Would be great if the support for Python syntax highlighting is added in Crucible review comments. Currenctly when wiki markup \{code:python} is used, it displays the following message below:-

{noformat}
Unable to find source-code formatter for language: python. Available languages are: actionscript, html, java, javascript, none, sql, xhtml, xml
{noformat}

No email template files have been modified, but a difference between older versions of FishEye/Crucible and 3.3.2 can be seen in the email subject.

Previous versions (such as 3.0.1 and 3.1.1) showed a different subject for each event, for example:
{noformat}
[Crucible] 2 comments added: (CR-1) My review
[Crucible] Everyone has finished reviewing: (CR-1) My review
{noformat}

However, I've upgraded those instances to to 3.3.2, and the email subjects in 3.3.2 are always like this:
{noformat}
[Crucible] CR-1: My review
{noformat}

Note that the event types {{2 comments added:}} and {{Everyone has finished reviewing:}} are not in the email subject lines post upgrading to 3.3.2.

Some customers are requesting this change to be reverted.

if review comment contains a link that happens to be a link to JIRA issue or Crucible review, it is rendered fine in Crucible web app, but only the issue key/review perm id is linked.  This causes links to be wrongly interpreted by gmail client for example.

For example comment https://fisheye.dev.internal.atlassian.com/cru/CR-FE-8479#c84221 contains text: https://fisheye.dev.internal.atlassian.com/cru/CR-FE-8516 which is rendered in HTML (and REST) as
{code:html}
https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/<a href="https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/FECRU-4720">FECRU-4720</a>
{code}
Because the first part (https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/) is recognised as gmail as URL alike it is rendered as a link, so in result I get this in gmail:
{code:html}
<a href="https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/" target="_blank">https://jira.atlassian.com/<wbr>browse/</a><a href="https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/FECRU-4720" target="_blank">
{code}
Notice the first <a> element navigates me to https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/ rather than to actual issue.

We could change the rendering so the whole URL is linked (if site matches) or first part is not rendered at all (just the issue key/perm id)?
